he results are independent of explicit values of\ndimensional parameters.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 Aug 2021 16:54:59 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 24 Dec 2021 05:42:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-28"}
{"id":"2108.13973","submitter":"Juan-Andr\\'es P\\'erez-R\\'ua","authors":"Juan-Andr\\'es P\\'erez-R\\'ua","title":"Solver-Free Heuristics to Retrieve Feasible Points for Offshore Wind\n  Farm Collection System","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SY cs.SY math.OC","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  A set of solver-free heuristics for the offshore wind collection system\nproblem are presented. Currently, methods of this type are not able to cope\nwith typical constraints, and most of their variations minimize only for\naccumulated cable length. The first algorithm is a two-steps decision process,\nwhere the output is the design of a tree network satisfying cable thermal\nlimits constraints, but vulnerable to violate planarity constraints.\nSubsequently, a cable crossings repair heuristic is introduced in order to fix\ninfeasible points from the first heuristic. Finally, a refining heuristic\n(negative cycle cancelling refining heuristic) takes over to improve feasible\npoints. The latter iteratively swaps cables, intending to find cycles with\nnegative costs that will lead to investment savings. The sequence of heuristics\nsupports the most important restrictions of the problem. The applicability of\nthe workflow is empirically demonstrated by means of a set of large-scale\nreal-world offshore wind farms. The numerical results indicate that: (i)\nfeasible points can be retrieved in computing times in order of seconds, and\n(ii) warm-starting can help solvers to converge significantly faster for\nproblems with solution time in order of several hours.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 Aug 2021 16:55:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-01"}
{"id":"2108.13974","submitter":"Matteo Fadel","authors":"Matteo Fadel and Lorenzo Maccone","title":"The time-energy uncertainty relation for quantum events","comments":"Comments are welcome","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.104.L050204","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Textbook quantum mechanics treats time as a classical parameter, and not as a\nquantum observable with an associated Hermitian operator. For this reason, to\nmake sense of usual time-energy uncertainty relations such as $\\Delta {t}\\Delta\nE\\gtrsim\\hbar$, the term $\\Delta t$ must be interpreted as a time interval, and\nnot as a time measurement uncertainty due to quantum noise. However, quantum\nclocks allow for a measurement of the \"time at which an event happens\" by\nconditioning the system's evolution on an additional quantum degree of freedom.\nWithin this framework, we derive here two {\\em true} uncertainty relations that\nrelate the uncertainty in the quantum measurement of the time at which a\nquantum event happens on a system to its energy uncertainty.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 Aug 2021 16:57:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-08"}
