data sample of approximately 3.8 billion\nisobar collisions of $^{96}_{44}$Ru+$^{96}_{44}$Ru and\n$^{96}_{40}$Zr+$^{96}_{40}$Zr at $\\sqrt{s_{\\rm NN}}=200$ GeV. Prior to the\nblind analysis, the CME signatures are predefined as a significant excess of\nthe CME-sensitive observables in Ru+Ru collisions over those in Zr+Zr\ncollisions, owing to a larger magnetic field in the former. A precision down to\n0.4% is achieved, as anticipated, in the relative magnitudes of the pertinent\nobservables between the two isobar systems. Observed differences in the\nmultiplicity and flow harmonics at the matching centrality indicate that the\nmagnitude of the CME background is different between the two species. No CME\nsignature that satisfies the predefined criteria has been observed in isobar\ncollisions in this blind analysis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Sep 2021 00:44:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-02"}
{"id":"2109.00132","submitter":"Sencun Zhu","authors":"Yuanyi Sun, Sencun Zhu, Yao Zhao, Pengfei Sun","title":"Let Your Camera See for You: A Novel Two-Factor Authentication Method\n  against Real-Time Phishing Attacks","comments":"12 pages, 17 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  Today, two-factor authentication (2FA) is a widely implemented mechanism to\ncounter phishing attacks. Although much effort has been investigated in 2FA,\nmost 2FA systems are still vulnerable to carefully designed phishing attacks,\nand some even request special hardware, which limits their wide deployment.\nRecently, real-time phishing (RTP) has made the situation even worse because an\nadversary can effortlessly establish a phishing website replicating a target\nwebsite without any background of the web page design technique. Traditional\n2FA can be easily bypassed by such RTP attacks. In this work, we propose a\nnovel 2FA system to counter RTP attacks. The main idea is to request a user to\ntake a photo of the web browser with the domain name in the address bar as the\n2nd authentication factor. The web server side extracts the domain name\ninformation based on Optical Character Recognition (OCR), and then determines\nif the user is visiting this website or a fake one, thus defeating the RTP\nattacks where an adversary must set up a fake website with a different domain.\nWe prototyped our system and evaluated its performance in various environments.\nThe results showed that PhotoAuth is an effective technique with good\nscalability. We also showed that compared to other 2FA systems, PhotoAuth has\nseveral advantages, especially no special hardware or software support is\nneeded on the client side except a phone, making it readily deployable.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Sep 2021 00:54:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-02"}
